---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ContentImage from '../../components/ContentImage.astro';
import canetoadCloseup from '../../assets/images/canetoad-closeup.jpg';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Cane Toad Eggs: Identification and Removal Guide for Florida"
  description="Cane toad eggs guide for Florida homeowners. Learn how cane toad egg strings look, where they appear, and what to do to reduce future toad populations."
>
  <div class="urgency">
    <strong>Pet owners:</strong> Egg findings often indicate active adult cane toads nearby. Keep dogs supervised and review the <a href="/cane-toad-dog-poisoning/">emergency guide</a>.
  </div>

  <div class="hero">
    <h1>Cane Toad Eggs: What They Look Like and What To Do</h1>
    <p>Cane toad eggs usually appear as long strands of dark beads in clear gel. Identifying and responding early helps reduce future cane toad activity around your home.</p>
    <a href="/cane-toad-removal/" class="btn btn-lg">Get Professional Removal Help -></a>
  </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h2>How To Identify Cane Toad Eggs</h2>
    <p>Cane toad eggs are laid in long strings, not compact clusters. They are commonly found in shallow, still water and may be mistaken for debris unless inspected closely.</p>

    <figure class="content-figure">
      <ContentImage
        src={canetoadCloseup}
        alt="Adult cane toad showing rough skin and large parotoid glands — breeding adults deposit egg strings in standing water nearby"
      />
      <figcaption>Finding eggs usually means active adults on or near your property; limit pet access to those water features until you have a plan.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Where Homeowners Usually Find Egg Strings</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Retention pond edges</li>
      <li>Decorative water features and low water basins</li>
      <li>Pool-adjacent puddles and drainage pockets</li>
      <li>Temporary standing water after rain</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why Early Action Matters</h2>
    <p>During warm months, cane toad reproduction can accelerate quickly. Early egg detection and habitat changes reduce the chance of repeated population spikes.</p>

    <h2>What To Do Next</h2>
    <p>Photograph findings, limit pet access to the area, and contact a provider if you are seeing adult cane toads consistently.</p>

    <h2>FAQ</h2>
    <div class="faq">
      <details><summary>Do cane toad eggs look like frog eggs?</summary><p>Not exactly. Cane toad eggs are usually in long connected strings rather than clumped masses.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Can egg findings predict more cane toads soon?</summary><p>Yes, egg strings usually indicate active breeding nearby.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Should I call a pro after finding eggs?</summary><p>If adult activity is recurring, professional removal and prevention planning are recommended.</p></details>
    </div>

    <p>Already seeing toads? <a href="/cane-toad-removal/">Connect with a removal pro -></a></p>
    <p>For species background, visit <a href="/cane-toad-florida/">Cane Toad Florida -></a>.</p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
